Lab 04 - User Role Can Be Modified in User Profile
Platform: PortSwigger Web Security Academy
Category: Access Control
Difficulty: Apprentice
Status: ✅ Solved

Objective
Exploit a Mass Assignment vulnerability to modify the authenticated user's role and gain administrator privileges.

Background
The application allows users to update their email address through a JSON request. The backend automatically maps incoming JSON properties to the user object without restricting which properties may be modified.

Methodology
Logged in as a normal user.
Navigated to My Account.
Updated the email address.
Intercepted the request using Burp Suite.
Sent the request to Repeater.
Observed the normal JSON body:
{
  "email":"test@example.com"
}
Modified the request:
{
  "email":"test@example.com",
  "roleid":2
}
Sent the modified request.
Successfully changed the user's role to Administrator.
Accessed the /admin endpoint.
Deleted the user carlos.
Verified successful completion of the lab.
Vulnerability
Mass Assignment (Auto-Binding)
The server automatically accepted additional JSON properties supplied by the client and updated security-sensitive fields.

Evidence
Original request:

{
  "email":"test@example.com"
}
Modified request:

{
  "email":"test@example.com",
  "roleid":2
}
Administrative action performed:

Deleted user: carlos
Impact
An attacker can:

Escalate privileges
Gain administrator access
Access restricted functionality
Modify or delete sensitive data
Fully compromise the application
Severity: Critical

Root Cause
The application trusted client-supplied JSON and automatically mapped all fields to the backend user object.

Security-sensitive attributes such as roleid should never be modifiable by users.

Remediation
Developers should:

Use allow-lists for accepted input fields.
Reject unexpected properties.
Store user roles on the server.
Validate authorization separately from profile updates.
Burp Suite Skills Practiced
Proxy
HTTP History
Repeater
JSON Manipulation
Parameter Tampering
Response Analysis
Pentester's Notes
The profile update request initially exposed only the email field.

By manually adding the hidden roleid property to the JSON request, administrator privileges were obtained through a Mass Assignment vulnerability.

Lessons Learned
Never trust client-supplied JSON.
Hidden fields can often be added manually.
Security-sensitive attributes must never be user-controllable.
Auto-binding frameworks can introduce severe privilege escalation vulnerabilities.
